## 🚫 **GLOBAL ANTI-CHEATING PROTOCOLS**

### **Code Quality Anti-Cheating Rules (MANDATORY)**
These rules apply to ALL code, not just tests:

- **DO NOT** refactor by simply moving code around without real separation of concerns
- **DO NOT** create modules with artificial separation (e.g., by line count only)
- **DO NOT** implement placeholder logic that returns hardcoded values
- **DO NOT** create fake implementations that don't perform real business logic
- **DO NOT** use deprecated patterns without updating to modern alternatives
- **DO NOT** create modules that can't be tested independently
- **DO NOT** skip work due to missing dependencies - fix the dependencies instead
- **DO NOT** use fallback mechanisms that hide real problems
- **DO NOT** create code that can be skipped - code must work or fail clearly

### **Implementation Quality Rules (MANDATORY)**
- **ALWAYS** implement real business logic, not placeholder functions
- **ALWAYS** ensure proper separation of concerns when refactoring
- **ALWAYS** use modern patterns and update deprecated code
- **ALWAYS** make code independently testable
- **NEVER** claim functionality works without actually implementing it
- **NEVER** provide fake solutions or incomplete implementations
- **NEVER** hide problems with fallback mechanisms

---

## ✅ **GLOBAL QUALITY STANDARDS**

### **Code Quality Principles**
- **Real Implementation**: All code must perform actual business logic, not return hardcoded values
- **Proper Separation**: Refactoring must create real separation of concerns, not just move code
- **Modern Patterns**: Use current best practices, not deprecated patterns
- **Testability**: All code must be independently testable
- **No Shortcuts**: Fix dependencies and problems, don't work around them
- **Clear Failures**: Code should fail clearly, not silently or with fallbacks

### **Quality Validation**
Before claiming any work is complete:
- [ ] Code performs real business logic (not placeholders)
- [ ] Refactoring creates real separation of concerns
- [ ] Modern patterns are used (no deprecated code)
- [ ] Code is independently testable
- [ ] Dependencies are fixed (not worked around)
- [ ] Failures are clear and explicit (no silent fallbacks)

